ve and motivation to the management team to give them the confidence to make the change. Sherpa provided the contacts, tenacity and flexibility to add value to the project from concept development to first sales. The process worked because of the development of the strategy and building the business case. The rapid growth was the ability of the team to execute the plan.\r\n\r\n<strong>Financial Modelling</strong>\r\nWith a capital high fronted the model investors need a robust plan to secure the high upfront cost of of funding. Attracting appropriate angel investment with the cultural fit and door opeing capability will be a further catalyst to rapid growth.\r\n\r\nContact Sherpa on <strong>0191 211 1995</strong> to arrange your free no obligation consultation. ', 'Atlas Infrastructure Management', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '168-revision-33', '', '', '2010-10-12 15:21:30', '2010-10-12 15:21:30', '', 168, 'http://www.sherpabusinessconsultancy.com/wordpress/business-consultancy/168-revision-33.html', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(621, 2, '2010-10-21 11:35:32', '2010-10-21 11:35:32', 'Sherpa were approached by a leading third sector organisation who were seeking strategic guidance as they entered a period of economic uncertainty. \n\nThe organisation embarked on a organisational development project with Sherpa to build a cohesive action plan to deal with a reduced budget and a commitment to focus on their core providing adequate service provision to vulnerable users.\n\n<strong>Background:</strong> The management team had identified a need for change due to impending budgetary cuts and were looking to create greater accountability through more streamlined business processes.\n\nThey also recognized the need to restructure the management team and to return to a focus on ‘core business’ to ensure that the services provided to their clients were not impacted by restricted finances.\n\n<strong>The solution:</strong> A new management structure allowed the business to focus on what the organisation was originally created to provide. With greater control, the business was in a strong position to deal with financial issues as they arose. Reconfiguring the financial structure meant that the business could strategically plan to cope with budget cuts, and the outsourcing of non-service related roles to specialist providers created greater accountability and a return to core business.\n\n\n\n', 'Third sector', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '272-autosave', '', '', '2010-10-21 11:35:32', '2010-10-21 11:35:32', '', 272, 'http://www.sherpabusinessconsultancy.com/wordpress/business-consultancy/272-autosave.html', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
